</tr>
</table>
<p>Matrices of this kind are useful because they can be easily added together to give the overall results of an election. The sum of all ballots in an election is called the sum matrix. Suppose that in the imaginary election there are two other voters. Their preferences are (D, A, C, B) and (A, C, B, D). Added to the first voter, these ballots would give the following sum matrix:</p>
<table border="1" align="center" width="175">
<tr>
<td colspan="2" rowspan="2" align="center"></td>
<th colspan="4" align="center">Opponent</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th>A</th>
<th>B</th>
<th>C</th>
<th>D</th>
</tr>
